President Joe Biden has announced his nominations for key roles in his administration. The nominees are Paul Monteiro for Director of the Community Relations Service at the Department of Justice, and Laura Ross for Member of the Board of Directors at the Corporation for Public Broadcasting.

Paul Monteiro currently serves as Chief of Staff to the President and Assistant Vice President of External Affairs at Howard University. He has a background in law and previously worked on Senator Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign. Monteiro has also served in various roles within the White House, including Associate Director in the Office of Public Engagement and National Director of AmeriCorps Volunteers in Service to America. He later headed the Community Relations Service at the Department of Justice.

Laura Ross is a retired attorney with a career in public service. She has held positions such as Corporation Counsel of the City of New York and Legislative Counsel to a New York State Senator. Ross has also served in government roles at the Civil Rights Division of the Department of Justice and as a Legislative Assistant to a U.S. Congressman. She has been involved in various organizations, including New York Public Media, WNYC Public Radio, and the Mayor's Fund to Advance New York City.

Both nominees bring extensive experience in public service and are expected to play important roles in their respective positions if confirmed.